 (/juːˈdʒɛnɪks/ yoo-JEN-iks; from Ancient Greek εύ̃ (eû) 'good, well' and -γενής (genḗs) 'born, come into being, growing/grown')[1]
 He concretely intended it to replace the word "stirpiculture", which he had used previously but which had come to be mocked due to its perceived sexual overtones.[43]
 Though the origins of the concept also had to do with certain interpretations of Mendelian inheritance and the theories of August Weismann.[47]: 335–336 
 He had identified eugenicists as a major obstacle to the eradication and cure of tuberculosis in his 1917 address "Consumption: Its Cause and Cure",[72]
 Despite Morgan's public rejection of eugenics, much of his genetic research was adopted by proponents of eugenics.[129][130]
 Similarly, the author Edwin Black has described potential "eugenics wars" as the worst-case outcome of eugenics.[page needed] In his view, this scenario would mean the return of coercive state-sponsored genetic discrimination and human rights violations such as the compulsory sterilisation of persons with genetic defects, the killing of the institutionalised and, specifically, the segregation and genocide of races which are considered inferior.[94]
Law professors George Annas and Lori Andrews have similarly argued that the use of these technologies could lead to such human-posthuman caste warfare.[143][144]

